# 🌦️ WeatherProject: My First Python Data App

Welcome! This is my very first educational project written in Python. I built it to learn how to work with real-world data, visualize results, and implement basic machine learning models.

## 🚀 Project Overview
The application fetches weather forecast data for selected cities (Bratislava, Prague, or Vienna) via an open API, analyzes temperature trends, and attempts to predict future values using a regression model.

The project includes two interfaces:
1. Console Interface (`main.py`): For quick analysis and data visualization.
2. Web Service (`app.py`): A Flask-based API that serves weather and prediction data in JSON format.

## 🛠️ Tech Stack & Skills
In this project, I applied several key data science libraries for the first time:
* Pandas: Used for structuring data into DataFrames and calculating statistics (mean, max, min).
* NumPy: Used for mathematical operations and data reshaping.
* Matplotlib: Used to generate charts showing temperature changes over time.
* Scikit-learn: I implemented my first AI model — Linear Regression — to predict upcoming weather trends.
* Flask: To wrap my logic into a functional web server.
* Requests: To handle external API calls and process JSON responses.

## 📈 What I Learned
* How to interact with external APIs and handle JSON data.
* Data cleaning and basic statistical analysis.
* Building visualizations that help understand data patterns.
* Understanding how a simple ML model "learns" from history to make predictions.

## ⚙️ How to Run
1. Clone the repository.
2. Install the required dependencies:
   pip install flask pandas matplotlib scikit-learn numpy requests
3. Run num.py for the console version or app.py to start the web server

